history.content:
Take 126 if you liked the probability portion of CS70 and are interested in learning more about probability and its applications in EECS.

Take 127 if you liked the optimization segments of 189 and would like to delve deeper into those specific topics.

I can assure you that neither of them would be redundant after 189, and many people do take those classes after 189 (especially 127).

In terms of workload, 126 has a HW pset every week while 127 has one due every 2 weeks; so make sure your other techs don't have weekly psets, unless you feel you can handle otherwise.

children.subject: I did 189 last fall, and then 126+127 last spring. 126+127 was heavy workload for me, but they have been my two favorite classes so far. I especially liked 127, that's one of the most important classes to take if you're interested in optimization and machine learning. I find 126 less useful for day to day applications, but still interesting material. 127 isn't necessarily redundant after 189 in my opinion, but this semester 189 ramped up a little and we started teaching a little bit of convexity and quite a bit of duality, so I suppose 127 could be a bit redundant. But 189 only scratched the surface of material in 127, and also you can never take "enough" optimization, so taking 127 will reinforce your understanding further.

history.content: The two most important courses for someone interested in machine learning are 126 and 127. They are fundamentally more important than 189. Ideally, students would take them before taking 189. But if you've taken 189, still take 126 and 127. For mathematical type material, if it turns out you didn't need to take it, the workload for that part will be small. So no harm done. If it takes you any time or effort, then you really needed to take the course.
How are these classes after taking 189 this semester? I'm taking both next semester with other technicals and was wondering if it's doable.
